1. Predictive Processing (how the brain is modeled)

A common theory in neuroscience is predictive processing. The brain is thought to work roughly like this:

Prediction of world state
        ↓
Compare prediction to sensory input
        ↓
Compute error (difference)
        ↓
Update model
        ↓
Repeat continuously

So the brain is basically a prediction machine trying to minimize surprise.

Key subsystems people identify:

Function	Brain role
Prediction	frontal cortex
Error detection	anterior cingulate
Salience/attention	parietal networks
Memory	hippocampus
Policy/action	basal ganglia

Notice something?

These are separable functional roles, not one giant blob.

⸻

2. What modern AI architectures are doing

Many current research directions are moving toward modular reasoning systems, because pure single-model reasoning struggles with complex tasks.

Typical components being explored:

AI Component	Purpose
Planner	long-term reasoning
Tool user	external computation
Memory store	persistent knowledge
Critic / verifier	check reasoning
Retriever	search information
Policy layer	choose actions

Again — functional specialization.

